ion, Cabrita shows how Zionists on either side of the Atlantic used the democratic resources of evangelical Christianity to stake out a place of belonging within rapidly-changing societies. In doing so, they laid claim to nothing less than the Kingdom of God. Today, the number of American Zionists is small, but thousands of independent Zionist churches counting millions of members still dot the Southern African landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aSpiritual healingzAfrica, Southern. 0aSpiritual healingzIllinoiszZion. 0aZionist churches (Africa)zAfrica, Southern. 0aZionist churches (Africa)zIllinoiszZionxHistoryy20th century. 0aZionist churches (Africa)zSouth AfricazJohannesburg. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674985780?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674985780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674985780/original  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles